text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!EndangeredLanguages]]%0a%0a!Irula Language%0a%0a:Author: shreya_r%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aDiscussion of the endangered Irula language in South India%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aIrula is a Dravidian language from the Tamil-Kannada subgroup spoken by the Irula people in the Nilgiri mountains. The language is very similar to Old Tamil with some influence from Kannada, and uses the Tamil writing system. It has around 12,000 speakers, and although its EGIDS classification is not available, Ethnologue lists it as a mid-sized endangered language with classification somewhere in the range 6b to 9, meaning that children no longer normally use and learn the language.%0a%0aDue to the close similarities to Tamil, some people argue that Irula is just a dialect and not its own language, contributing to some stigma around its use. This is partially because it is considered a more crude and less prestigious dialect due to its influence from other South Indian languages. Thus, Irula people typically do not speak the language outside of their own communities. They still use the language when practicing cultural traditions such as the dance and music performed in rituals, but this is mostly upheld by elderly members of the tribe. Their practices and language have been changing over time due to influence from other groups. However, funding has been put into revitalization programs, though I was unable to find specific information about such programs.%0a%0ahttps://www.ethnologue.com/language/iru%0ahttps://indiantribalheritage.org/?p=30724#gsc.tab=0%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a#foxbegin 210507-161148-390820#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!An Irula Folksong %0a-> - sanjana_m%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aWhen I was younger, I actually visited an area in which people spoke this language, and at the time, I did not know that it was different than Tamil, which was spoken in all the surrounding areas. After reading this article, I was curious to see if I could find any examples of the language online. Sadly, there are little to no resources that could help somebody learn the language easily accessible on line, and after searching for audio/video clips of the spoken language, I couldn't find anything. However, I did find some songs in the Irula language, one of which I have linked below.%0a%0ahttps://youtu.be/ZGD2_qndYk0%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210507-161148-390820#%0a#foxbegin 210509-030234-804670#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!An Irula Movie  %0a-> - sgangu%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aI could not find nearly as much Irula content as I could for other South Indian languages. However, I did find that an Irula movie was directed in 2019, which is quite surprising. It is the first Indian film in history to use this language. I've linked a song from the movie below. After listening to it, I'd say that it sounds quite similar to Tamil and other Dravidian languages, so I can see how it might be considered another dialect and not another language entirely. %0a%0ahttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nIx7rDsrENs%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210509-030234-804670#%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a(:section: B:)%0a(:Category: EndangeredLanguages:)
